#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.11.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:5
msgid ""
"This release supports Python 2.6 - 2.7 and 3.2 - 3.5 and contains a number "
"of enhancements and improvements. Note also the build system changes listed "
"below as they may have subtle effects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:9
msgid ""
"No Windows (TM) binaries are provided for this release due to a broken "
"toolchain. One of the providers of Python packages for Windows (TM) is your "
"best bet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:15
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:17
msgid "Details of these improvements can be found below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:19
msgid "The datetime64 type is now timezone naive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:20
msgid "A dtype parameter has been added to ``randint``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:21
msgid "Improved detection of two arrays possibly sharing memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:22
msgid "Automatic bin size estimation for ``np.histogram``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:23
msgid "Speed optimization of A @ A.T and dot(A, A.T)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:24
msgid "New function ``np.moveaxis`` for reordering array axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:28
msgid "Build System Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:30
msgid ""
"NumPy now uses ``setuptools`` for its builds instead of plain distutils. "
"This fixes usage of ``install_requires='numpy'`` in the ``setup.py`` files "
"of projects that depend on NumPy (see gh-6551).  It potentially affects the "
"way that build/install methods for NumPy itself behave though.  Please "
"report any unexpected behavior on the NumPy issue tracker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:35
msgid "Bento build support and related files have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:36
msgid "Single file build support and related files have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:40
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:42
msgid "The following changes are scheduled for NumPy 1.12.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:44
msgid "Support for Python 2.6, 3.2, and 3.3 will be dropped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:45
msgid ""
"Relaxed stride checking will become the default. See the 1.8.0 release notes "
"for a more extended discussion of what this change implies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:47
msgid ""
"The behavior of the datetime64 \"not a time\" (NaT) value will be changed to "
"match that of floating point \"not a number\" (NaN) values: all comparisons "
"involving NaT will return False, except for NaT != NaT which will return "
"True."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:51
msgid "Indexing with floats will raise IndexError, e.g., a[0, 0.0]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:53
msgid ""
"Indexing with non-integer array_like will raise ``IndexError``, e.g., "
"``a['1', '2']``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:55
msgid ""
"Indexing with multiple ellipsis will raise ``IndexError``, e.g., "
"``a[..., ...]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:57
msgid ""
"Non-integers used as index values will raise ``TypeError``, e.g., in "
"``reshape``, ``take``, and specifying reduce axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:61
msgid "In a future release the following changes will be made."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:63
msgid ""
"The ``rand`` function exposed in ``numpy.testing`` will be removed. That "
"function is left over from early NumPy and was implemented using the Python "
"random module.  The random number generators from ``numpy.random`` should be "
"used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:67
msgid ""
"The ``ndarray.view`` method will only allow c_contiguous arrays to be viewed "
"using a dtype of different size causing the last dimension to change.  That "
"differs from the current behavior where arrays that are f_contiguous but not "
"c_contiguous can be viewed as a dtype type of different size causing the "
"first dimension to change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"Slicing a ``MaskedArray`` will return views of both data **and** mask. "
"Currently the mask is copy-on-write and changes to the mask in the slice do "
"not propagate to the original mask. See the FutureWarnings section below for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:79
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:82
msgid "datetime64 changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:83
msgid ""
"In prior versions of NumPy the experimental datetime64 type always stored "
"times in UTC. By default, creating a datetime64 object from a string or "
"printing it would convert from or to local time::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:87
msgid ""
"# old behavior\n"
">>> np.datetime64('2000-01-01T00:00:00')\n"
"numpy.datetime64('2000-01-01T00:00:00-0800')  # note the timezone offset "
"-08:00"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:92
msgid ""
"A consensus of datetime64 users agreed that this behavior is undesirable and "
"at odds with how datetime64 is usually used (e.g., by `pandas <http://pandas."
"pydata.org>`__). For most use cases, a timezone naive datetime type is "
"preferred, similar to the ``datetime.datetime`` type in the Python standard "
"library. Accordingly, datetime64 no longer assumes that input is in local "
"time, nor does it print local times::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:99
msgid ""
">>> np.datetime64('2000-01-01T00:00:00')\n"
"numpy.datetime64('2000-01-01T00:00:00')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:102
msgid ""
"For backwards compatibility, datetime64 still parses timezone offsets, which "
"it handles by converting to UTC. However, the resulting datetime is timezone "
"naive::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:106
msgid ""
">>> np.datetime64('2000-01-01T00:00:00-08')\n"
"DeprecationWarning: parsing timezone aware datetimes is deprecated;\n"
"this will raise an error in the future\n"
"numpy.datetime64('2000-01-01T08:00:00')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:111
msgid ""
"As a corollary to this change, we no longer prohibit casting between "
"datetimes with date units and datetimes with time units. With timezone naive "
"datetimes, the rule for casting from dates to times is no longer ambiguous."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:116 ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:319
msgid "``linalg.norm`` return type changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:117
msgid ""
"The return type of the ``linalg.norm`` function is now floating point "
"without exception.  Some of the norm types previously returned integers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:121
msgid "polynomial fit changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:122
msgid ""
"The various fit functions in the numpy polynomial package no longer accept "
"non-integers for degree specification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:126
msgid "*np.dot* now raises ``TypeError`` instead of ``ValueError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:127
msgid ""
"This behavior mimics that of other functions such as ``np.inner``. If the "
"two arguments cannot be cast to a common type, it could have raised a "
"``TypeError`` or ``ValueError`` depending on their order. Now, ``np.dot`` "
"will now always raise a ``TypeError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:133
msgid "FutureWarning to changed behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:135
msgid ""
"In ``np.lib.split`` an empty array in the result always had dimension "
"``(0,)`` no matter the dimensions of the array being split. This has been "
"changed so that the dimensions will be preserved. A ``FutureWarning`` for "
"this change has been in place since Numpy 1.9 but, due to a bug, sometimes "
"no warning was raised and the dimensions were already preserved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:143
msgid "``%`` and ``//`` operators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:144
msgid ""
"These operators are implemented with the ``remainder`` and ``floor_divide`` "
"functions respectively. Those functions are now based around ``fmod`` and "
"are computed together so as to be compatible with each other and with the "
"Python versions for float types.  The results should be marginally more "
"accurate or outright bug fixes compared to the previous results, but they "
"may differ significantly in cases where roundoff makes a difference in the "
"integer returned by ``floor_divide``. Some corner cases also change, for "
"instance, NaN is always returned for both functions when the divisor is "
"zero, ``divmod(1.0, inf)`` returns ``(0.0, 1.0)`` except on MSVC 2008, and "
"``divmod(-1.0, inf)`` returns ``(-1.0, inf)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:156
msgid "C API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"Removed the ``check_return`` and ``inner_loop_selector`` members of the "
"``PyUFuncObject`` struct (replacing them with ``reserved`` slots to preserve "
"struct layout). These were never used for anything, so it's unlikely that "
"any third-party code is using them either, but we mention it here for "
"completeness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:166
msgid "object dtype detection for old-style classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:168
msgid ""
"In python 2, objects which are instances of old-style user-defined classes "
"no longer automatically count as 'object' type in the dtype-detection "
"handler. Instead, as in python 3, they may potentially count as sequences, "
"but only if they define both a `__len__` and a `__getitem__` method. This "
"fixes a segfault and inconsistency between python 2 and 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:175
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:177
msgid ""
"``np.histogram`` now provides plugin estimators for automatically estimating "
"the optimal number of bins. Passing one of ['auto', 'fd', 'scott', 'rice', "
"'sturges'] as the argument to 'bins' results in the corresponding estimator "
"being used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:182
msgid ""
"A benchmark suite using `Airspeed Velocity <https://asv.readthedocs.io/>`__ "
"has been added, converting the previous vbench-based one. You can run the "
"suite locally via ``python runtests.py --bench``. For more details, see "
"``benchmarks/README.rst``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:187
msgid ""
"A new function ``np.shares_memory`` that can check exactly whether two "
"arrays have memory overlap is added. ``np.may_share_memory`` also now has an "
"option to spend more effort to reduce false positives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:191
msgid ""
"``SkipTest`` and ``KnownFailureException`` exception classes are exposed in "
"the ``numpy.testing`` namespace. Raise them in a test function to mark the "
"test to be skipped or mark it as a known failure, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:195
msgid ""
"``f2py.compile`` has a new ``extension`` keyword parameter that allows the "
"fortran extension to be specified for generated temp files. For instance, "
"the files can be specified to be ``*.f90``. The ``verbose`` argument is also "
"activated, it was previously ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:200
msgid ""
"A ``dtype`` parameter has been added to ``np.random.randint`` Random "
"ndarrays of the following types can now be generated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:203
msgid "``np.bool_``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:204
msgid "``np.int8``, ``np.uint8``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:205
msgid "``np.int16``, ``np.uint16``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:206
msgid "``np.int32``, ``np.uint32``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "``np.int64``, ``np.uint64``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:208
msgid "``np.int_``, ``np.intp``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:210
msgid ""
"The specification is by precision rather than by C type. Hence, on some "
"platforms ``np.int64`` may be a ``long`` instead of ``long long`` even if "
"the specified dtype is ``long long`` because the two may have the same "
"precision. The resulting type depends on which C type numpy uses for the "
"given precision. The byteorder specification is also ignored, the generated "
"arrays are always in native byte order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:217
msgid ""
"A new ``np.moveaxis`` function allows for moving one or more array axes to a "
"new position by explicitly providing source and destination axes. This "
"function should be easier to use than the current ``rollaxis`` function as "
"well as providing more functionality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:222
msgid ""
"The ``deg`` parameter of the various ``numpy.polynomial`` fits has been "
"extended to accept a list of the degrees of the terms to be included in the "
"fit, the coefficients of all other terms being constrained to zero. The "
"change is backward compatible, passing a scalar ``deg`` will behave as "
"before."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:228
msgid ""
"A divmod function for float types modeled after the Python version has been "
"added to the npy_math library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:233
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:236
msgid "``np.gradient`` now supports an ``axis`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:237
msgid ""
"The ``axis`` parameter was added to ``np.gradient`` for consistency.  It "
"allows to specify over which axes the gradient is calculated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:241
msgid "``np.lexsort`` now supports arrays with object data-type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:242
msgid ""
"The function now internally calls the generic ``npy_amergesort`` when the "
"type does not implement a merge-sort kind of ``argsort`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:246
msgid "``np.ma.core.MaskedArray`` now supports an ``order`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:247
msgid ""
"When constructing a new ``MaskedArray`` instance, it can be configured with "
"an ``order`` argument analogous to the one when calling ``np.ndarray``. The "
"addition of this argument allows for the proper processing of an ``order`` "
"argument in several MaskedArray-related utility functions such as ``np.ma."
"core.array`` and ``np.ma.core.asarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:254
msgid "Memory and speed improvements for masked arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:255
msgid ""
"Creating a masked array with ``mask=True`` (resp. ``mask=False``) now uses "
"``np.ones`` (resp. ``np.zeros``) to create the mask, which is faster and "
"avoids a big memory peak. Another optimization was done to avoid a memory "
"peak and useless computations when printing a masked array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:261
msgid "``ndarray.tofile`` now uses fallocate on linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:262
msgid ""
"The function now uses the fallocate system call to reserve sufficient disk "
"space on file systems that support it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:266
msgid "Optimizations for operations of the form ``A.T @ A`` and ``A @ A.T``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:267
msgid ""
"Previously, ``gemm`` BLAS operations were used for all matrix products. Now, "
"if the matrix product is between a matrix and its transpose, it will use "
"``syrk`` BLAS operations for a performance boost. This optimization has been "
"extended to ``@``, ``numpy.dot``, ``numpy.inner``, and ``numpy.matmul``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:272
msgid ""
"**Note:** Requires the transposed and non-transposed matrices to share data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:275
msgid "``np.testing.assert_warns`` can now be used as a context manager"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:276
msgid "This matches the behavior of ``assert_raises``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "Speed improvement for np.random.shuffle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:280
msgid "``np.random.shuffle`` is now much faster for 1d ndarrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:284
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:287
msgid "Pyrex support was removed from ``numpy.distutils``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:288
msgid ""
"The method ``build_src.generate_a_pyrex_source`` will remain available; it "
"has been monkeypatched by users to support Cython instead of Pyrex.  It's "
"recommended to switch to a better supported method of build Cython "
"extensions though."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:294
msgid "``np.broadcast`` can now be called with a single argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:295
msgid ""
"The resulting object in that case will simply mimic iteration over a single "
"array. This change obsoletes distinctions like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:298
msgid "if len(x) == 1:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:299
msgid "shape = x[0].shape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:301
msgid "else:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:301
msgid "shape = np.broadcast(\\*x).shape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:303
msgid "Instead, ``np.broadcast`` can be used in all cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:306
msgid "``np.trace`` now respects array subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:307
msgid ""
"This behavior mimics that of other functions such as ``np.diagonal`` and "
"ensures, e.g., that for masked arrays ``np.trace(ma)`` and ``ma.trace()`` "
"give the same result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:312
msgid "``np.dot`` now raises ``TypeError`` instead of ``ValueError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:313
msgid ""
"This behavior is now consistent with other functions such as ``np.inner``. "
"If the two arguments cannot be cast to a common type, it could have raised a "
"``TypeError`` or ``ValueError`` depending on their order. Now, ``np.dot`` "
"will now always raise a ``TypeError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:320
msgid ""
"The ``linalg.norm`` function now does all its computations in floating point "
"and returns floating results. This change fixes bugs due to integer overflow "
"and the failure of abs with signed integers of minimum value, e.g., "
"int8(-128). For consistency, floats are used even where an integer might "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:327
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:330
msgid "Views of arrays in Fortran order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:331
msgid ""
"The F_CONTIGUOUS flag was used to signal that views using a dtype that "
"changed the element size would change the first index. This was always "
"problematical for arrays that were both F_CONTIGUOUS and C_CONTIGUOUS "
"because C_CONTIGUOUS took precedence. Relaxed stride checking results in "
"more such dual contiguous arrays and breaks some existing code as a result. "
"Note that this also affects changing the dtype by assigning to the dtype "
"attribute of an array. The aim of this deprecation is to restrict views to "
"C_CONTIGUOUS arrays at some future time. A work around that is backward "
"compatible is to use ``a.T.view(...).T`` instead. A parameter may also be "
"added to the view method to explicitly ask for Fortran order views, but that "
"will not be backward compatible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:344
msgid "Invalid arguments for array ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:345
msgid ""
"It is currently possible to pass in arguments for the ``order`` parameter in "
"methods like ``array.flatten`` or ``array.ravel`` that were not one of the "
"following: 'C', 'F', 'A', 'K' (note that all of these possible values are "
"both unicode and case insensitive). Such behavior will not be allowed in "
"future releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:352
msgid "Random number generator in the ``testing`` namespace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:353
msgid ""
"The Python standard library random number generator was previously exposed "
"in the ``testing`` namespace as ``testing.rand``. Using this generator is "
"not recommended and it will be removed in a future release. Use generators "
"from ``numpy.random`` namespace instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:359
msgid "Random integer generation on a closed interval"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:360
msgid ""
"In accordance with the Python C API, which gives preference to the half-open "
"interval over the closed one, ``np.random.random_integers`` is being "
"deprecated in favor of calling ``np.random.randint``, which has been "
"enhanced with the ``dtype`` parameter as described under \"New Features\". "
"However, ``np.random.random_integers`` will not be removed anytime soon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:368
msgid "FutureWarnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:371
msgid "Assigning to slices/views of ``MaskedArray``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:372
msgid ""
"Currently a slice of a masked array contains a view of the original data and "
"a copy-on-write view of the mask. Consequently, any changes to the slice's "
"mask will result in a copy of the original mask being made and that new mask "
"being changed rather than the original. For example, if we make a slice of "
"the original like so, ``view = original[:]``, then modifications to the data "
"in one array will affect the data of the other but, because the mask will be "
"copied during assignment operations, changes to the mask will remain local. "
"A similar situation occurs when explicitly constructing a masked array using "
"``MaskedArray(data, mask)``, the returned array will contain a view of "
"``data`` but the mask will be a copy-on-write view of ``mask``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.11.0-notes.rst:383
msgid ""
"In the future, these cases will be normalized so that the data and mask "
"arrays are treated the same way and modifications to either will propagate "
"between views. In 1.11, numpy will issue a ``MaskedArrayFutureWarning`` "
"warning whenever user code modifies the mask of a view that in the future "
"may cause values to propagate back to the original.  To silence these "
"warnings and make your code robust against the upcoming changes, you have "
"two options: if you want to keep the current behavior, call ``masked_view."
"unshare_mask()`` before modifying the mask.  If you want to get the future "
"behavior early, use ``masked_view._sharedmask = False``. However, note that "
"setting the ``_sharedmask`` attribute will break following explicit calls to "
"``masked_view.unshare_mask()``."
msgstr ""
